SIMPLE: frith
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frith
<hw>Frith</hw> <pr>(fr⟦icr⟧th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>firth</ets>, Icel. <ets>fj⟦oum⟧r⟦edh⟧r</ets>; akin to Sw.
<ets>fj⟦aum⟧rd</ets>, Dan. <ets>fiord</ets>, E. <ets>ford</ets>.
⟦root⟧78. See <er>Ford</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Firth</er>,
<er>Fiord</er>, <er>Fret</er> a frith, <er>Port</er> a
harbor.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>A narrow arm of the sea; an
estuary; the opening of a river into the sea; <as>as, the <ex>Frith</ex>
of Forth</as>. Also called <altname>firth</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of weir for catching fish.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frith</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frith
<hw>Frith</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>frith</ets> peace,
protection, land inclosed for hunting, park, forest, AS.
<ets>fri⟦edh⟧</ets> peace; akin to <ets>freno⟦edh⟧</ets> peace,
protection, asylum, G. <ets>friede</ets> peace, Icel.
<ets>fri⟦edh⟧r</ets>, and from the root of E. free, friend. See
<er>Free</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Affray</er>,
<er>Defray</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A forest; a woody place.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small field taken out of a common, by inclosing
it; an inclosure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir J.
Wynne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frithy</ent>⟦br⟧
